y charts the diverse and often conflicting interests, itineraries and experiences of commercial and political elites, common seamen and stewardesses, and Islander dock workers and passengers.Drawing on a variety of sources, including shipping company archives, imperial conference proceedings, diaries, newspapers and photographs, this book will appeal to cultural historians and geographers of British imperialism, scholars of transport and mobility studies, and historians of New Zealand and the Pacific.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aShippingzOceaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aShippingzOceaniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSteam-navigationzPacific OceanxHistory. 0aSteamboat lineszNew ZealandxHistory. 0aSteamboatszPacific AreaxHistory. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aFiji.  aFirst World War.  aLascar Act.  aSuva.  aUSSCo.  acoal face.  acrew culture.  aimperial transport.  alabour market.  amanagerial capitalism.  amaritime dominance.  amaritime transport operations.  aocean liners.  asavages.  aseamen.  asteamship operations.  astewardesses.  atrading networks.  atranspacific trades.  awharf labourers.1 aSteel, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611919340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119193/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles